One of the most significant events that occurred in Western Sahara in the past 20 years is the escalation of tensions and the subsequent outbreak of the Western Sahara conflict in 2020. This conflict has been ongoing for several decades, but tensions reached a critical point in November 2020 when the Polisario Front, a Sahrawi rebel national liberation movement, declared the end of a 29-year ceasefire with Morocco.

The conflict revolves around the territorial dispute between Morocco and the Polisario Front, which seeks independence for Western Sahara. Morocco claims sovereignty over the region, while the Polisario Front demands a referendum on self-determination for the Sahrawi people. The United Nations has been involved in mediating the conflict through its peacekeeping mission, the United Nations Mission for the Referendum in Western Sahara (MINURSO).

The resumption of hostilities in 2020 led to a series of clashes between Moroccan forces and the Polisario Front, resulting in casualties on both sides. The situation also led to a significant increase in tensions between Morocco and Algeria, which supports the Polisario Front. Several countries, including the United States, recognized Morocco's sovereignty over Western Sahara, further complicating the situation.

This recent escalation in the Western Sahara conflict has brought renewed attention to the long-standing issue and has highlighted the need for a peaceful resolution to the dispute.
